  "prompt": "Why are people who are half-black and half-white generally simply referred to as \"black\"?",
  "response": "This phenomenon is rooted in the historical concept of the \"one-drop rule\" in the United States, which originated during the era of slavery and segregation. According to this racist social and legal principle, a person with any trace of African ancestry was considered black, regardless of their physical appearance or predominant racial background. This rule was used to maintain racial segregation and white supremacy. \n\nToday, while the one-drop rule is no longer legally enforced, its cultural legacy persists. Many mixed-race individuals may choose to identify as black due to:\n\n1. Social perception and treatment\n2. Cultural identification\n3. Personal choice\n4. Historical context of racial discrimination\n\nHowever, it's important to note that many mixed-race individuals now embrace more nuanced racial identities and reject being categorized solely as black.",
